  1. Given the symptoms exhibited in a patient and a database of anonymized patient records, predict whether the patient is likely to have an illness (Parkinson’s disease). A model of this decision problem could be used by a program to provide decision support to medical professionals.

    You can follow the following steps :

    • Data Analysis

    • Data Preprocessing

    • Data Standardization

    • Model Training

    • Measure your model’s accuracy.

    a. Use 80% of samples as training data size.

    • Build a predictive system to verify that the model built is able to predict the patient’s Parkinson’s disease with one instance of the dataset.

You can download the Dataset from: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/470/parkinson+s+disease+classification

Summary

In this analysis, we worked with a dataset containing speech features from 188 patients with Parkinson's Disease (107 men and 81 women) and a control group of 64 healthy individuals (23 men and 41 women). The data was collected from the Department of Neurology in the Cerrahpaşa Faculty of Medicine, Istanbul University. The dataset included 754 attributes that represent various speech signal processing algorithms applied to the speech recordings of Parkinson's Disease (PD) patients.

We followed these steps:

  1. Data Loading: We loaded the data from the provided CSV file.

  2. Data Cleaning: We checked for missing values and duplicate rows in the dataset. There was one duplicate row, which we removed.

  3. Data Analysis: We generated descriptive statistics and a correlation matrix for the dataset to understand the range, distribution, and relationships between different variables in the data. We also visualized the distribution of the target variable (class) in the dataset.

  4. Data Preprocessing: We scaled the features using standardization, excluding the 'gender' and 'class' columns as they are binary categorical variables.

  5. Data Splitting: We split the data into a training set (70% of the data) and a test set (30% of the data).

  6. Model Training: We trained a Logistic Regression model and a Decision Tree model using the training data.

  7. Model Evaluation: We evaluated the models using the test data. The Logistic Regression model achieved an accuracy of approximately 84.58% on the test data, while the Decision Tree model achieved an accuracy of approximately 83.70%.

  8. Gender Analysis: We analyzed the performance of the Logistic Regression model separately for male and female patients. The model's accuracy was slightly higher for female patients (85.96%) compared to male patients (83.19%).

  9. Feature Importance: We identified the top 10 features that contributed most to the predictions of the Logistic Regression model. We also calculated the correlation matrix for these top features to understand their relationships.

  10. Visualization: We visualized the distribution of the target variable, the top feature importances, and the correlations between the top features.

Conclusion

My analysis showed that both the Logistic Regression model and Decision Tree model could predict Parkinson's disease status with fairly high accuracy using the speech features in the dataset. However, the Logistic Regression model slightly outperformed the Decision Tree model in terms of accuracy.

The Logistic Regression model had slightly higher accuracy for female patients than for male patients. This suggests that the model may be picking up on some gender-specific characteristics in the speech features that are related to Parkinson's disease. However, more investigation would be needed to confirm this.
